I am a big fan of <a href='http://memcached.org/'>Memcached</a> and recently built a class that stores database queries to memcached simply and with scalability.  

Here's the hypothetical problem that this class solves:  

Traffic to your site has been growing quickly and burdening your database and now your existing database queries just won't cut it anymore and now you want to let Memcached lighten the load with it's awesome memory caching system.  

You have lots of different calls to different database elements and need a flexible class that 1. checks if the data is already in memcached, 2. if not it grabs it from the database, then 3. Stores the data in memcached for future use, thus limiting the call to the database and promoting faster and more reliable performance.  

Well this php class does just that in a memcached enabled environment (it even checks to make sure memcached is available!).  

Ok let's do this.

Make sure you have Memcached enabled on your server.  To check this, just run the script:

<pre class='prettyprint'>
&lt;?php
/* 
You are actually checking for Memcache
Care to find out more on why this is, you can check out this forum post: http://serverfault.com/questions/63383/memcache-vs-memcached
*/

if(class_exists('Memcache')){
  // Memcache is enabled.
  echo "Sure is Bob";
} else {
   echo "No way Jose";
}
?&gt;
</pre>

If you don't have it installed, there are lots of articles out there that will help you install it on your particular machine.  If you are installing onto a a CentOS Linux Server like myself, I found this article helpful: <a href='http://mrphp.com.au/blog/install-memcache-cpanel-running-centos'>http://mrphp.com.au/blog/install-memcache-cpanel-running-centos</a>.

And now after all this is setup and configured properly, we can built our class.

Here is the class:

<pre class='prettyprint'>
&lt;?php
// Memcache connection constants
define('MEMCACHED_HOST', '127.0.0.1');
define('MEMCACHED_PORT', '11211');

class MemcacheItem{
        //// Sets the memcache item with a key
	function cacheAvailable(){
		// Connection creation
		$memcache = new Memcache;
		return $memcache->connect(MEMCACHED_HOST, MEMCACHED_PORT);
	}

        function set($key, $itemArray){
		
		// Connection creation
		$memcache = new Memcache;
		// And we ask Memcached to set the data
		if($this->cacheAvailable()) $memcache->set($key, $itemArray);
		
	}
        //// Gets the memcache item by its key	
	function get($key){
		
		// Connection creation
		$memcache = new Memcache;
		// And we ask Memcached to get the data
		if($this->cacheAvailable()) return $memcache->get($key);
		
	}
        //// Deletes the memcache by its key
	function delete($key){
		
		// Connection creation
		$memcache = new Memcache;
		// And we ask Memcached to delete the data
		if($this->cacheAvailable()) $memcache->delete($key);
		
	}
        //// Query memcache first, then the database
	function dbMemeQuery($table, $field, $id){
		
		/// Memcache 
		$memcache = new Memcache;
		$cacheAvailable = $memcache->connect(MEMCACHED_HOST, MEMCACHED_PORT);
		$key = $table . '-' . $field . '-' . $id;
        //// Make sure memcache available
		if($this->cacheAvailable()){
			
		 	$tableArr = $memcache->get($key);
		
		}
        //// Query memcache first, then return if true
		if($tableArr[$field]){
			
			return $tableArr[$field];
			
		} else {
        //// Query database and store value for later use
			$sql = "SELECT $field FROM $table WHERE id = '$id'"; 
			$result = mysql_query($sql);
			
			if(mysql_num_rows($result)!==0){
				
				$value = mysql_result($result,0);
			
				$itemArray = array($field => $value);
				
				$this->set($key,$itemArray);
				
				return $value;
			}
		
		}
	}

}
//// Set this class for use
$memcacheItem = new MemcacheItem;
?&gt;
</pre>


Then we add the new class to our existing Database calling Class
<pre class='prettyprint'>
&lt;?php
/*
This class queries the cache first with values for table, field and uid from the database
assuming we already have a database table for users with a field of city
that has a value of Dallas, TX
*/
class User {

	function city($uid){
		
		$memcacheItem = new MemcacheItem;
                return $memcacheItem->dbMemeQuery('users', 'city', $uid); /// Returns our value
	
	}
}
$user = new User;
echo $user->city(1); /// Returns Dallas, TX
?&gt;
</pre>
This will return Dallas, TX and store to the cache the memcached key "users-city-1" with value Dallas, TX so until this data is updated or deleted, it will always return Dallas, TX and never have to query the database.

To delete this value <strong>just from the cache</strong> run this:
<pre class='prettyprint'>
&lt;?php
$memcache->delete('users-city-1');
?&gt;
</pre>

And there you have it!  You can now store your database calls to the server's memory through Memcahced and serve up that data much faster and with less load on the DB server.

